ovember 29, 1733. Three years earlier, her brother Elizur Talcott had married Hezekiah's first cousin Ruth Wright. Two Wright cousins married two Talcott siblings — children of Deacon Benjamin Talcott and grandchildren of John Hollister's line on both sides."}],"artworks":[],"documents":[],"quotes":[],"statues":[],"research_tags":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"landmarks":[],"institutions":[],"research_sources":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Mehitabel Talcott","first_name":"Mehitabel","last_name":"Talcott","married_names":[]},"residence":{},"military_service":[],"slug":"mehitabel-talcott-1713"},"T00135":{"id":"T00135","has_descendants_documented":true,"classification":{"is_talcott_descendant":true,"include_in_path_calculation":true,"generation_from_john_talcott":2,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":true,"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"birth":{"year":1674,"month":3,"day":1,"city":"Wethersfield","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"death":{"year":1727,"month":11,"day":12,"city":"Glastonbury","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"parents":{"father_id":"T00036","mother_id":"U00025"},"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"U00030","children_ids":["T00454","T00455","T00456","T00457","T00458","T00459","T00460","T00461"],"marriage_number":1,"end_type":"death_of_spouse","end_year":1715,"date_year":1699,"date_month":1,"date_day":5},{"children_ids":[],"spouse_id":"U00044","marriage_number":2}],"tags":["deacon","named_for_ancestor"],"sources":[{"short":"Talcott 1876","page":"Entry 435"}],"burial":{"plot_notes":"Green Cemetery, Glastonbury, Hartford County, Connecticut."},"will":{"dated":"1727-10-13","proved":"1727-11-12","summary":"Will of Lt. Benjamin Talcott, Glastonbury CT. Wife: £80 + use of parlor, cellar, garret, ovens, gardens, one-third of orchard and land west of highway to great river — during widowhood only. Son Benjamin: lands in Bolton + 124 acres Hebron (bought of Joseph and John Phelps). Son John: 300 acres Hebron (west of Jacob Root), 50 acres Hebron (north of Richard Curtis), one yoke of steers, £10 moveable, + £15 from Elizur. Son Samuel: south half of home lot, 153 acres beyond Black Ledge River (Glastonbury/Hebron border), half undivided Glastonbury lands, smith-shop with all smithery tools, longest gun, half team. Son Elizur: north half of home lot with all buildings (except smith-shop), 60 acres Ash Swamp Glastonbury, 96 acres near bare hill Glastonbury, other half undivided lands, newest gun, half team — he to pay John £15. Daughter Sarah: £100. Daughter Hannah: £100 + decent suit of clothes or £10. Daughter Mehitabel: £100 + decent suit of clothes or £10. Executors: son-in-law Jonathan Hale and son Benjamin Talcott. Witnesses: Samuel Smith Jr., Nathaniel Talcott, Thomas Wells. Estate inventory: £2563 15s. 8d.","note":"Will text reproduced in Talcott Pedigree (1876) pp.106-109."},"gender":"male","number_of_marriages":2,"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"cross_connections":[{"type":"family_connection","related_id":"T01806","display_label":"Glastonbury homestead passed intact to him 175 years later.","link_text":"Jared G. Talcott"}],"baptism":{},"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"legacy","header":"His house bore bullet marks until 1854","body":"He built a fortified wooden house on Main Street, Glastonbury in 1699 — a refuge from Indian attacks for the surrounding community. The house bore bullet marks until it was taken down soon after 1854."},{"number":2,"category":"marriage","header":"Wife Sarah died in childbed at thirty-four","body":"Sarah Hollister, granddaughter of original 1636 Hartford settler John Hollister, married him in 1699 and bore him eight children. She died in childbirth at the homestead October 15, 1715."},{"number":3,"category":"legacy","header":"Sons signed Bolton's 1731 founding patent","body":"Two of his sons Benjamin and Nathaniel were listed as Bolton Proprietors in the 1731 patent, signed by their cousin Governor Joseph Talcott. A third son Elizur later chaired Glastonbury's denunciation of the Boston Port Bill."},{"number":4,"category":"family","header":"Two Wright cousins married two Talcott siblings","body":"His son Elizur married Ruth Wright; his daughter Mehitabel married Ruth's first cousin Hezekiah Wright. Two Wright cousins thus married two Talcott siblings, weaving the families together."},{"number":5,"category":"legacy","header":"Farm in family from 1643 through 1876","body":"His grandfather John Talcott had bought the Glastonbury farm from Samuel Sherman and Richard Gildersleeve in 1643. The land was still owned by descendant Jared G. Talcott in 1876."}],"bio":{"display_name":"Deacon Benjamin Talcott","title":"Deacon","first_name":"Benjamin","last_name":"Talcott","married_names":[]},"residence":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"slug":"benjamin-talcott-1674"},"U00030":{"id":"U00030","visible_default":false,"in_talcott_book":true,"classification":{"is_spouse_of_talcott_descendant":true,"include_in_path_calculation":true,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"birth":{"year":1676,"month":10,"day":25,"city":"Wethersfield","state":"Connecticut"},"death":{"year":1715,"month":10,"day":15},"parents":{"father_id":"Y00006","mother_id":"Y00007"},"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"T00135","children_ids":["T00454","T00455","T00456","T00457","T00458","T00459","T00460","T00461"],"marriage_number":1,"date_year":1699,"date_month":1,"date_day":5}],"sources":[{"short":"Talcott 1876","page":"Entry 435"}],"burial":{"plot_notes":"Green Cemetery, Glastonbury, Hartford County, Connecticut."},"gender":"female","tags":["died_in_childbirth"],"number_of_marriages":1,"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Sarah Hollister Talcott","first_name":"Sarah","last_name":"Talcott","married_names":["Talcott"],"maiden_name":"Hollister"},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"death","header":"She died in childbed; the baby followed","body":"Sarah Hollister married Deacon Benjamin Talcott and died in childbed at Glastonbury in 1715, at thirty-eight. The daughter whose birth she did not survive, Abigail, lived only eighteen days more."}],"slug":"sarah-hollister-1676"}},"burialCemetery":null,"institutionsById":{},"crossConnections":[]}